## The `.map()` pattern

Every list you have ever seen in a web app -- a list of emails, search results, shopping cart items, team members -- follows the same React pattern: take an array of data and transform it into an array of components using `.map()`.

Here is the simplest possible example:

```jsx
function FruitList() {
  const fruits = ["Apple", "Banana", "Cherry"];

  return (
    <ul>
      {fruits.map(fruit => (
        <li key={fruit}>{fruit}</li>
      ))}
    </ul>
  );
}
```

This renders:
- Apple
- Banana
- Cherry

Let us break down what is happening:

1. `fruits` is an array of three strings
2. `.map()` goes through each item in the array and transforms it
3. For each fruit, the function `fruit => (<li key={fruit}>{fruit}</li>)` creates a list item
4. The result is an array of three `<li>` elements, which React renders inside the `<ul>`

Think of `.map()` as a machine: data goes in one end, components come out the other end. One item in, one component out.

### A realistic example

In real apps, you are usually mapping over an array of objects, not simple strings:

```jsx
function TeamDirectory() {
  const members = [
    { id: 1, name: "Alice Johnson", role: "Engineer", department: "Platform" },
    { id: 2, name: "Bob Smith", role: "Designer", department: "Product" },
    { id: 3, name: "Carol Davis", role: "PM", department: "Growth" },
  ];

  return (
    <div className="team-directory">
      <h2>Team Members</h2>
      {members.map(member => (
        <div key={member.id} className="member-card">
          <h3>{member.name}</h3>
          <p>{member.role} - {member.department}</p>
        </div>
      ))}
    </div>
  );
}
```

This renders three member cards. Each card shows a different person's name, role, and department. The data is different, but the structure is identical -- that is the power of `.map()`.

Notice the pattern: inside `.map()`, you have access to each individual item. The parameter name (`member` in this case) is just a variable name -- you could call it anything. It represents one item from the array on each pass.

### The `key` prop: why it matters

Every example above includes a `key` prop on the mapped elements. This is not optional -- it is a React requirement. The `key` tells React which item is which, so it can efficiently update the list when items are added, removed, or reordered.

```jsx
// Good: unique ID as key
{members.map(member => (
  <div key={member.id}>{member.name}</div>
))}

// Bad: array index as key
{members.map((member, index) => (
  <div key={index}>{member.name}</div>
))}
```

Why is the array index bad? Because indexes change when items are reordered, added, or removed. If you delete the second item, the third item gets index 1 (previously 2), and React thinks it is the same item -- leading to bugs where the wrong data appears in the wrong place.

The rule: **always use a unique, stable identifier as the key**. Database IDs are ideal. If the data does not have IDs, any property that uniquely identifies each item works.

Here is what happens without proper keys -- a common AI-generated code mistake:

```jsx
// AI-generated code often does this:
{tasks.map((task, index) => (
  <TaskItem key={index} task={task} />
))}

// You should tell the AI to fix it:
{tasks.map(task => (
  <TaskItem key={task.id} task={task} />
))}
```

### Mapping to custom components

In real codebases, the JSX inside `.map()` is usually a custom component:

```jsx
function ProductGrid({ products }) {
  return (
    <div className="product-grid">
      {products.map(product => (
        <ProductCard
          key={product.id}
          name={product.name}
          price={product.price}
          imageUrl={product.imageUrl}
          inStock={product.inStock}
        />
      ))}
    </div>
  );
}
```

This is the same pattern: `.map()` transforms each product object into a `<ProductCard />` component, passing the relevant data as props. The `ProductCard` component (defined elsewhere) handles how each card looks.

### Combining `.map()` with conditionals

You will often see `.map()` combined with the conditional patterns from Module 2.3:

```jsx
function TaskList({ tasks }) {
  return (
    <div>
      <h2>Tasks</h2>
      {tasks.length > 0 ? (
        <ul>
          {tasks.map(task => (
            <li key={task.id} className={task.done ? "completed" : ""}>
              {task.title}
              {task.urgent && <span className="urgent-badge">Urgent</span>}
            </li>
          ))}
        </ul>
      ) : (
        <p>No tasks yet. Add one to get started.</p>
      )}
    </div>
  );
}
```

Reading this:
1. If `tasks.length > 0`, render the task list (ternary pattern)
2. Each task is mapped to an `<li>` with a unique key
3. Completed tasks get a "completed" CSS class (conditional class pattern)
4. Urgent tasks get an extra badge (`&&` pattern)
5. If there are no tasks, show an empty state message

This combination of `.map()`, ternaries, and `&&` is the bread and butter of React rendering. Once you can read these three patterns together, you can read most React components.

### Filtering before mapping

Sometimes you need to show only some items from an array. The `.filter()` method is often chained before `.map()`:

```jsx
function ActiveMembers({ members }) {
  return (
    <ul>
      {members
        .filter(member => member.isActive)
        .map(member => (
          <li key={member.id}>{member.name}</li>
        ))}
    </ul>
  );
}
```

Read this as: "Take the members array, keep only the active ones, then turn each active member into a list item." The `.filter()` runs first, creating a smaller array. Then `.map()` transforms that filtered array into JSX.

### Reading `.map()` in the wild

Here is a realistic dashboard component you might encounter:

```jsx
function RecentOrders({ orders }) {
  return (
    <table className="orders-table">
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Order #</th>
          <th>Customer</th>
          <th>Total</th>
          <th>Status</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        {orders.map(order => (
          <tr key={order.id}>
            <td>{order.orderNumber}</td>
            <td>{order.customerName}</td>
            <td>${order.total.toFixed(2)}</td>
            <td>
              <span className={`status status-${order.status}`}>
                {order.status}
              </span>
            </td>
          </tr>
        ))}
      </tbody>
    </table>
  );
}
```

Even though this is a table instead of a list, the pattern is identical: `.map()` transforms each order object into a table row. Each row has a unique `key` (the order ID). The status gets a conditional CSS class based on its value.

